{
    "ocr_text": "UNITED BROTHERHOOD OF CARPENTERS AND JOINERS OF AMERICA,
COPY.
Indianapolis, Ind., May 14, 1909.
Mr. Samuel Gompers, President,
American Federation of Labor,
801-809 G St., N.W.,
Washington, D. C.
Dear Sir and Brother:
Enclosed herewith you will find copy of communication
received from our local union #50 Portland, Oregon, containing
reasons why they are not affiliated with the Central Labor Council
in that city. It is very evident that our local union is ready
and willing to give its support and co-operation to the Portland
Central Body but in return for same they expect at least a square
deal at the hands of that body. I therefore hope that you will
investigate complaints contained in this letter to the end that
harmony and good feelings may prevail among all organizations concerned.
With best wishes and kindest regards, I am,
Fraternally yours,
(Signed) Frank Duffy,
General Secretary.",
    "summary": "The letter, dated May 14, 1909, from Frank Duffy of the United Brotherhood of Carpenters and Joiners of America, informs Samuel Gompers, President of the American Federation of Labor, about a communication from the local union in Portland, Oregon. The local union explains their non-affiliation with the Central Labor Council and emphasizes their willingness to co-operate if treated fairly. Duffy requests an investigation to ensure harmony among organizations.",
    "date": "1909-05-14",
    "is_printed": true,

}
